node.text:
We are proud to announce the launch of The Dogist Fund, our new philanthropic giving initiative. The Dogist is committed to the greater good of the entire dog community, and The Dogist Fund will serve this important mission in new ways. The Dogist Fund will empower non-profit work worldwide in the areas of dog rescue, rehabilitation, and working dogs – 100% of the funds raised will be put towards these programs.

When The Dogist first began in 2013, we introduced ‘Give a Dog a Bone’, a program that allowed our audience to sponsor individual adoptable dogs. Then in 2019, after launching The Dogist Shop, we introduced ‘Feeding Friends’, which donated 20,091 meals to rescue dogs in need. Additionally, through social media campaigns and rescue rides, we have helped find homes for more than 1,000 dogs and raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for animal rescue causes worldwide.

The Dogist Fund will take our charitable giving to the next level with a more comprehensive and intentional approach to canine welfare. By harnessing the power of our partners, our large dog-loving community, as well as being supported by a portion of our own bottom line, we know the fund will have a meaningful impact for the wellbeing of dogs individually and at large. We hope you will join us in supporting The Dogist Fund initiative as we develop it and help dogs and their people live better lives together around the world! To learn more about The Dogist Fund, or to make a donation, visit the link in our bio.

node.text: Zanmi & Rodney, Pitt Bull (2 y/o), Centereach, NY • “I have my whole life because of dogs – my house, my job, my joy. I met my wife walking dogs, actually. They walked me right into her.  We have a shared love of dogs in common. We have to love dogs like they love us, and feed them good, fresh food. And be patient. Always patient.” • A special series in partnership with @thefarmersdog

node.text: Cowboy, Golden Retriever (10 m/o), Cousins Island, Yarmouth, ME • “There was a fishing pole on the side of the boat and he wouldn't stop sniffing it. He loves fish so much. That night we saw something on him that looked like a stray whisker. I went to pull it off and realized it was a piece of fishing line attached to a hook that was through his lip – fully lodged in there. They had to sedate him and push it all the way through to get it out. He’s going to the Golden Retriever Nationals soon. He’s gonna compete in the 12-18 month class. It’s basically Disneyland for Golden Retrievers. His cousin and dad are going. He’s excited but he’s playing it cool.” @cowboy_ontherun

node.text: Theodore & Arya – Guide Dogs in training @guidingeyes, Labrador Retriever & German Shepherd (2 & 3 y/o), Croton-on-Hudson, NY • “Theodore and Aria are in the final stages of completing guide dog training and are strong candidates to be placed with a blind or visually impaired applicant of ours. Their goal is to travel safely, fluidly and effectively with their handler. Working together as a team, their handler will get more independence, confidence, and it opens them up socially. Everyone says, ‘OMG, what a beautiful dog!’, so it helps them be more social and approachable. With a cane you’re tapping back and forth, it physically moves people out of the way and you feel every little thing. With a dog, you go around them. It’s more fluid. It’s not for everyone, though. It’s a very big lifestyle change. You have a companion that goes everywhere you go. For first time handlers, a Labrador is very easily adaptable – they can snore and just hang out with you at a desk. You’ll say, ‘Ok bud, let’s go’, and they’re like, ‘Oh, cool!’ Shepherds are much more ‘Why are we sitting still? Let’s go.’ Two modes – sleep and go. Shepherds take some finesse. I’ve personally trained about 75 dogs and we highly encourage continued connection and networking with our graduates and their raisers. With some organizations, once you hand them off the relationship ends. We keep in touch to make sure everything’s going fine. Community and graduate support is a huge part of it. It takes a village to raise a puppy – genetics, breedings, whelping, early socialization, puppy classes. It’s all about community and connection, which also helps the dog with the transition. The graduations are heartwarming and fulfilling. All of the time and effort in training the dog formally has worked and will massively change someone’s life. The first couple days in class the dog may turn around and cry, like ‘You were my buddy!’ But you help facilitate the bond between them and their handler and limit it between yourself and the dog. I basically show them that they have the cookies.” If you missed our latest episode of @thedogistpodcast with @guidingeyes, head to the link in bio!

node.text: Danielle, Guide dog in training @guidingeyes – Labrador Retriever (6 w/o), Patterson, NY • “It all begins with the breeding. We have a genetics department with 90 to 100 active females and 20-30 active studs at any time. Breeding is done very carefully with a purpose. The first few weeks after the puppies are born are very calm. It's soft and sweet and quiet. They get puppy massaged twice a day so they get used to human contact. At five and a half weeks they’re weaned off mom and they go to the enrichment side where there’s a lot more activity. Two important things guide dogs need to do is look up and walk backwards – they don't do that naturally. There’s a suspension bridge, toys, ramps, stairs, and tunnels. We play sounds like kettles whistling and sirens so that they can be familiar with everything. We put on funny hats and glasses to get them used to unusual people. At six weeks and two days they go to a person’s home to get them used to a home environment – a vacuum cleaner, dishwasher, etc. They have a checklist to keep track of their progress. After this they come to our kennel – we call it kindergarten. They do solo-crating and expose them to more intense things, like mirrors, metal, pom-poms blowing in the wind, sound systems, etc. We play everything from heavy metal to classical music. They love Disney movies – Little Mermaid is their favorite. We’re constantly exposing them to different sounds, scents, and textures. We want to build that reference library. Every time they do this they get an evaluation, which goes in our database. We’re looking to see if the puppy has any issues or things to work on. You can see in their eyes when they start to learn – they’re so smart. We try to get as much information into their little brains as possible.” Head to the link in bio to listen to our latest podcast episode with the @guidingeyes team!

node.text: Riggs, English Bulldog (4 y/o), FDNY Engine 58/Ladder 26 - Harlem, New York, NY • “We don’t have any dogs at home since our jobs don’t allow for it, so Riggs is our collective dog. Being a firefighter is super tough and stressful. He definitely brings company morale up. We got crushed last night on some calls and having him to play with when we got back was so therapeutic. He’s not phased by the alarms one bit. The whole neighborhood knows him and is obsessed with him. He was born as the runt of his litter, so he has definitely leveled up as the big man on campus, or should I say firehouse.” @firefactoryriggs

node.text: Therapy dog Olive, Shih tzu mix (5 y/o), Hassenfeld Children’s Hospital at NYU Langone, New York, NY • “A lot of the time the kids don’t want to get up out of their hospital bed – they often have tubes in their stomach. But they will want to get up to walk for a dog. The dogs definitely improve outcomes for our patients. Time to mobilization is often shorter. There are papers about it – reduction in heart rate and blood pressure. The more relaxed you are, the better you feel, and there’s no price tag on that. We put Olive on a girl’s bed and she immediately opened her eyes. The girl didn’t even notice how hard it was to get up and walk because of Olive. Recovery is more likely if you can get a patient up and moving. We know how traumatic it can be for patients – kids really need to know that the MRI machine isn’t going to eat them. They will imagine much worse. We have to put everything in place for their medical and mental health. When a kid doesn’t want to go home we know we’ve done our job. And the therapy dogs are as much for us as they are for the kids and families. It lifts our spirits and keeps us going. We can do our best work when we’re feeling resilient. They make a huge impact for the staff, especially in the ICU.” @olive.my.luv • We’re teaming up with @thefarmersdog to help Hassenfeld Children’s Hospital at NYU Langone expand its pet therapy program – head to the link in our bio to find out how to donate to this life-changing program!
